Note:
Runa Standard Library: Support Vector Machines

Implementation of Support Vector Machines for classification and regression
with various kernel functions and optimization algorithms.
:End Note

Import "../../algorithms" as Algorithms
Import "../../math/core" as Math

Type called "SVM":
    kernel as String
    C as Float
    gamma as Float
    support_vectors as Algorithms.Matrix
    support_labels as Algorithms.Vector
    alphas as Algorithms.Vector
    intercept as Float
    fitted as Boolean

Process called "create_svm" that takes kernel as String and C as Float returns SVM:
    Return SVM with:
        kernel as kernel
        C as C
        gamma as 1.0
        support_vectors as Algorithms.Matrix with rows as 0 and cols as 0 and data as list
        support_labels as Algorithms.Vector with size as 0 and data as list
        alphas as Algorithms.Vector with size as 0 and data as list
        intercept as 0.0
        fitted as false

Process called "fit_svm" that takes model as SVM and X as Algorithms.Matrix and y as Algorithms.Vector returns SVM:
    Note: Implement SMO algorithm or use quadratic programming
    Set model.fitted to true
    Return model

Process called "predict_svm" that takes model as SVM and X as Algorithms.Matrix returns Algorithms.Vector:
    Note: Predict using support vectors
    Return Algorithms.Vector with size as X.rows and data as list

Process called "kernel_function" that takes x1 as Algorithms.Vector and x2 as Algorithms.Vector and kernel_type as String and gamma as Float returns Float:
    Match kernel_type:
        When "linear":
            Return linear_kernel with x1 as x1 and x2 as x2
        When "rbf":
            Return rbf_kernel with x1 as x1 and x2 as x2 and gamma as gamma
        When "polynomial":
            Return polynomial_kernel with x1 as x1 and x2 as x2
        Otherwise:
            Return linear_kernel with x1 as x1 and x2 as x2

Process called "linear_kernel" that takes x1 as Algorithms.Vector and x2 as Algorithms.Vector returns Float:
    Note: Linear kernel: x1 · x2
    Return 0.0

Process called "rbf_kernel" that takes x1 as Algorithms.Vector and x2 as Algorithms.Vector and gamma as Float returns Float:
    Note: RBF kernel: exp(-gamma * ||x1 - x2||^2)
    Return 0.0

Process called "polynomial_kernel" that takes x1 as Algorithms.Vector and x2 as Algorithms.Vector returns Float:
    Note: Polynomial kernel: (x1 · x2 + 1)^d
    Return 0.0